Practical No 1

Title : Import the legacy data from different sources and load in the target system.


1A) Importing Data from OData Feed

You import data into Power BI Desktop from the sample Northwind OData feed at the following URL, which you can copy (and then paste) in the steps below: http://services.odata.org/V3/Northwind/Northwind.svc/


  1. From the Home ribbon tab, select Get Data.

  2. Browse to the OData Feed data source.

  3. In the OData Feed dialog box, paste the URL for the Northwind OData feed and Select OK.


  4. In the Navigator pane, select the Customers, Products , Orders , Order_Details and Categories tables and click on Load.

  5. In the Fields Window of the PowerBI Desktop, the newly loaded tables are displayed



1B) Importing Data from Excel

  1. From the Home ribbon tab, select Get Data.

  2. Select the Excel data source.


  3. Browse to the location and select the required Excel file( Superstore)


  4. In the Navigator tab, select the tables that you want to import( Orders table in this case)

1C) Importing a CSV(Comma Separated value) File

  1. From the Home ribbon tab, select Get Data.

  2. Select the Text/CSV data source.



  3. Browse to the location and select the required CSV file( SalesJan2009)

  4. In the window that pops up just check your data and click on the Load Button.

    Practical No 2

    Title :Perform the Extraction Transformation and Loading (ETL) process to construct the database in the Power BI.


    Power BI Desktop includes Power Query Editor, which is where you shape and transform your data connections.Power Query Editor opens automatically when you select Edit from Navigator. You can also open the Power Query Editor by selecting Edit Queries / Transform data from the Home ribbon in Power BI Desktop.


    2A) Transformation on the Northwind Database

    Perform ETL transformation on the Northwind dataset and display the transformed schema.


    1. Open the pbix file where the Northwind dataset is imported(Prac 1A).In the Home Ribbon select the Transform data menu and click on Transform data.The Power Query Editor will open up


    2. In the Queries section select the Categories table. In the Home ribbon click on Choose Columns. In the drop-down list select CategoryID, CategoryName and Description.

    3. In the Queries section select the Customers table. In the Home ribbon click on Choose Columns. In the drop-down list select CustomerID and ContactName.


    4. In the Queries section select the Orders table. In the Home ribbon click on Choose Columns. In the drop-down list select OrderID, OrderDate, ShipCity and ShipCountry.


    5. In the Queries section select the Products table. In the Home ribbon click on Choose Columns. In the drop-down list select ProductID, ProductName and CategoryID.


    6. In the Queries section select the Order_Details table. Expand the Order column and select CustomerID. Rename the column Orders.CustomerID to CustomerID by double-clicking on the column name.


    7. Feature Extraction: In the Order_details table we have UnitPrice and Quantity that do not offer much insight. So we construct a feature called LineTotal using these two features. In the Add Column ribbon, click on Custom Column. In the window that opens up, write the formula/query by double clicking on the relevant available columns to create the new column and assign a name to it.



    8. Once all the transformations are done go to File and click on close and apply.

    9. In the PowerBI desktop, the updated tables will be displayed in the Fields view.

    10. In the PowerBI desktop click on the Modelling tab and select Manage relationships. It can be seen that the relationships between the five tables are automatically created. If any change is required, click on the edit button and make the changes manually(Note: If the transformation process is correctly implemented, no editing is required).

    11. In the PowerBI desktop go to the Model view.The schema representing the five tables will be displayed.

2B) Transformation on Superstore( Excel) data


Perform ETL transformation on the above dataset by converting the sales from US currency to Indian currency.


  1. Open the pbix file where the Excel(Superstore) dataset is imported(Prac 1B). In the

    Home Ribbon select the Transform data menu and click on Transform data.The Power Query Editor will open up.

  2. In the Queries view select the Orders table.

  3. In the Add Column ribbon, click on Custom Column. In the window that opens up, write the formula/query by double clicking on the relevant available columns to create the new column and assign a name to it.


  4. Once all the transformations are done click on close and apply.

2C) Transformation on SalesJan2009( CSV) data


Perform ETL transformation on the above dataset by converting the attribute name from lowercase to uppercase.

  1. Open the pbix file where the CSV(SalesJan2009) dataset is imported(Prac 1C). In the Home Ribbon select the Transform data menu and click on Transform data.The Power Query Editor will open up.

  2. In the Power Query Editor the data columns will be displayed.Select the column â€˜Nameâ€™. Go to the Transform tab and select Format. In the drop down select UPPERCASE.

  3. Once all the transformations are done click on close and apply.

Practical No 3 Title :Data Visualization from ETL process


Open the transformed Northwind dataset. Apply the following visualizations on the data:

  1. In the Fields tab, expand the Products table and select Product name.Expand the Order_Details table and select Quantity. The Quantity by ProductName data

    table will be displayed.


  2. In the Visualizations section, select the Clustered column chart to view the graphical representation of Quantity by ProductName data.


  3. Click anywhere in the canvas and select the Map visual. Expand the Products table and select Product name.Expand the Order_Details table and select Quantity. Expand the Orders table and select ShipCountry.


  4. Expand the Categories table, drag and drop the CategoryName field into Filters on this Page. Filter the data on the basis of categories. See the change in the visuals on the canvas.

  5. Click anywhere in the canvas and select a Pie Chart from the Visualizations.

    Expand the Products table and select Product name.Expand the Order_Details table and select Quantity.


  6. Select on any of the visualizations and see its effect on the other visualizations.


  7. Click anywhere in the canvas and select a Line Chart from the Visualizations. Expand the Products table and select Product name.Expand the Order_Details table and select Quantity.


  8. Expand the OrderDetails table and add LineTotal in Filters on this page. Apply the LineTotal filter and see the change in the Visualizations.

Practical No 5 Title: Prediction using Linear Regression


The steps to create the relationship is -

  • Carry out the experiment of gathering a sample of observed values of height and corresponding weight.

  • Create a relationship model using the lm() functions in R.

  • Find the coefficients from the model created and create the mathematical equation using these

  • Get a summary of the relationship model to know the average error in prediction. Also called residuals.

  • To predict the weight of new persons, use the predict() function in R.


    Methods used:

    lm()

    This function creates the relationship model between the predictor and the response variable.

    Syntax

    The basic syntax for lm() in linear regression is: lm(formula,data)

    Following is the description of the parameters used :

  • formula is a symbol presenting the relation between x and y.

  • data is the vector on which the formula will be applied.


    predict() Syntax

    The basic syntax for predict() in linear regression is : predict(object, newdata)

    Following is the description of the parameters used :

  • object is the formula which is already created using the lm() function.

  • newdata is the vector containing the new value for the predictor variable.


abline()

The R function abline() can be used to add vertical, horizontal or regression lines to a graph.

//Input Data

> Height <- c(151, 174, 138, 186, 128, 136, 179, 163, 152, 131)

> Weight <- c(63, 81, 56, 91, 47, 57, 76, 72, 62, 48)

# Create a training set consisting of 105 observations from the dataset.

  • input <- readingSkills[c(1:105),]


    # Build a classification tree using the ctree function

  • output <- ctree(nativeSpeaker ~ age + shoeSize + score, input)


    # Plot the classification tree

  • plot(output)


    # Inference :

    If score <= 38.306 and age > 6 , then not a nativeSpeaker

    If 30.766 < score <= 38.306 and age <= 6 , then a nativeSpeaker If score <= 30.766 and age <= 6 , then not a nativeSpeaker

    If score > 38.306 , then 70 % of those tested are nativeSpeaker shoeSize does not seem to have any impact on the dependent variable


    Note: The decision tree is highly sensitive to the training set chosen. The tree varies as the training set changes.

    # Build a Logistic model on the training set using the glm function, that will be used for prediction on the test set.

    The '.' indicates all the independent variables in the training dataset. 'binomial' is used in cases where the dependent

    variable takes only two values( 1 or 0). link=logit is the mathematical formulation.


  • model <- glm(survived ~.,family=binomial(link=logit),data=train)

  • summary(model) Call:

    # From the above result, we can see that pclass, sex and age have minimum p- values. So, technically only these variables directly

    affect the probability of a passenger's survival.


    # Now let's use the model that we've built to predict the value of 'survived' for all the observations in the test set. We use the predict function.It will

    return the probability(between 0.0 - 1.0) of 'survived'.


  • pred <- predict(model, test, type= "response")


    # y_pred is the value that will be predicted by the model. If the probability(pred) > 0.5, then the model predicts that a passenger has survived(1), else the passenger is predicted to be dead(0)


  • y_pred <- ifelse(pred > 0.5, 1, 0)


    # y_act is the actual value of 'survived' for the observations in the test set


  • y_act <- test$survived

    # To check how our model has fared in efficiently predicting the value of the dependent variable( survived ), we plot a confusion matrix of actual vs predicted.

  • table(y_act,y_pred) y_pred

211 passengers who were predicted to be dead, actually died (True Negative)

121 passengers who were predicted to have survived, actually survived (True Positive)

37 passengers who were predicted to have survived, actually died (False Positive)

52 passengers who were predicted to be dead, actually survived (False Negative)

Practical 10

Title: Data Modelling and Analytics with Pivot Table in Excel


Data Model is used for building a model where data from various sources can be combined by creating relationships among the data sources. A Data Model integrates the tables, enabling extensive analysis using PivotTables, Power Pivot, and Power View.


A Data Model is created automatically when you import two or more tables simultaneously from a database. The existing database relationships between those tables is used to create the Data Model in Excel.

Step 1 âˆ’ Open a new blank Workbook in Excel. Step 2 âˆ’ Click on the DATA tab.

Step 3 âˆ’ In the Get External Data group, click on the option From Access. The Select Data Source dialog box opens.

Step 4 âˆ’ Select Olympics.accdb, Events Access Database file.


Step 6 âˆ’ Tables in a database are similar to the tables in Excel. Check the â€˜Enable selection of multiple tablesâ€™ box, and select all the tables. Then click OK.

Step 7 âˆ’ The Import Data window appears. Select the PivotTable Report option. This option imports the tables into Excel and prepares a PivotTable for analyzing the imported tables. Notice that the checkbox at the bottom of the window - â€˜Add this data to the Data Modelâ€™ is selected and disabled.

Step 8 âˆ’ The data is imported, and a PivotTable is created using the imported tables.


Explore Data Using PivotTable

Step 1 âˆ’ You know how to add fields to PivotTable and drag fields across areas. Even if you are not sure of the final report that you want, you can play with the data and choose the best-suited report.


In PivotTable Fields, click on the arrow beside the table - Medals to expand it to show the fields in that table. Drag the NOC_CountryRegion field in the Medals table to the COLUMNS area.


Step 2 âˆ’ Drag Discipline from the Disciplines table to the ROWS area.


Step 3 âˆ’ Filter Discipline to display only five sports: Archery, Diving, Fencing, Figure Skating, and Speed Skating. This can be done either in PivotTable Fields area, or from the Row Labels filter in the PivotTable itself.

Step 4 âˆ’ In PivotTable Fields, from the Medals table, drag Medal to the VALUES area.

Step 5 âˆ’ From the Medals table, select Medal again and drag it into the FILTERS area.

Step 6 âˆ’ Click the dropdown list button to the right of the Column labels.

Step 7 âˆ’ Select Value Filters and then select Greater Thanâ€¦ Step 8 âˆ’ Click OK.

The Value Filters dialog box for the count of Medals is greater than appears.


Step 9 âˆ’ Type 80 in the Right Field. Step 10 âˆ’ Click OK.

The PivotTable displays only those regions, which has more than total 80 medals.


Create Relationship between Tables


Relationships let you analyze your collections of the data in Excel, and create interesting and aesthetic reports from the data you import.

Step 1 âˆ’ Insert a new Worksheet.

Step 2 âˆ’ Create a new table with new data. Name the new table as Sports.


Step 3 âˆ’ Now you can create relationship between this new table and the other tables that already exist in the Data Model in Excel. Rename the Sheet1 as Medals and Sheet2 as Sports.

On the Medals sheet, in the PivotTable Fields List, click All. A complete list of available tables will be displayed. The newly added table - Sports will also be displayed.

Step 4 âˆ’ Click on Sports. In the expanded list of fields, select Sports. Excel messages you to create a relationship between tables.

Step 5 âˆ’ Click on CREATE. The Create Relationship dialog box opens.


Step 6 âˆ’ To create the relationship, one of the tables must have a column of unique, non-repeated, values. In the Disciplines table, SportID column has such values. The table Sports that we have created also has the SportID column. In Table, select Disciplines.

Step 7 âˆ’ In Column (Foreign), select SportID. Step 8 âˆ’ In Related Table, select Sports.

Step 9 âˆ’ In Related Column (Primary), SportID gets selected automatically. Click OK.

Step 10 âˆ’ The PivotTable is modified to reflect the addition of the new Data Field Sport. Adjust the order of the fields in the Rows area to maintain the Hierarchy. In this case, Sport should be first and Discipline should be the next, as Discipline will be nested in Sport as a

sub-category.
